INSERT INTO agent_knowledge (content, summary, agent, category, confidence, source, created_by) VALUES
('SaaS magic number formula: Net New ARR / Sales & Marketing Spend from prior quarter. A magic number above 0.75 indicates efficient growth and justifies increasing S&M spend. Between 0.5-0.75, optimize before scaling. Below 0.5, there is a fundamental efficiency problem. Track this monthly with a 3-month rolling average to smooth seasonality. Best-in-class SaaS companies achieve 1.0-1.5.', 'SaaS magic number: >0.75 scale aggressively, 0.5-0.75 optimize, <0.5 fundamental problem', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.95, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('The Rule of 40 for SaaS: Revenue Growth Rate + EBITDA Margin should equal or exceed 40%. A company growing at 60% with -20% margins (score: 40) is healthy. A company growing at 20% with 10% margins (score: 30) is underperforming. Top quartile SaaS companies score 50+. For agencies, modify this to Revenue Growth Rate + Operating Margin, targeting a score of 35+ due to lower scalability.', 'Rule of 40: growth rate + EBITDA margin >= 40% for healthy SaaS, 35+ for agencies', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('LTV:CAC ratio benchmarks for SaaS: healthy is 3:1 to 5:1. Below 3:1, you are spending too much to acquire. Above 5:1, you are likely under-investing in growth and leaving market share on the table. Calculate LTV as: (ARPU × Gross Margin) / Monthly Churn Rate. Include all costs in CAC: ads, sales salaries, commission, tools, and overhead allocation. The payback period should be under 12 months for SMB SaaS.', 'LTV:CAC ratio: 3:1 to 5:1 healthy, payback under 12 months for SMB SaaS', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.96, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Agency financial model: target 60-70% gross margin on services (revenue minus direct labor costs). Net margin target is 15-25%. The most profitable agencies maintain a revenue-per-employee of 150-200K€. Below 100K€/employee, the agency is overstaffed or underpricing. Contractor-heavy models can achieve 75% gross margins but cap at 40% of revenue to maintain quality control.', 'Agency finance: 60-70% gross margin target, 150-200K€ revenue per employee', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('SaaS cohort analysis methodology: track each monthly signup cohort separately for 12+ months. Calculate cohort-level metrics: Month 1 activation rate, Month 3 retention rate (target >80%), Month 12 retention rate (target >65%), and Net Revenue Retention (NRR). NRR above 100% means expansion revenue exceeds churned revenue. Best-in-class NRR is 120-140%. Below 90% NRR signals a fundamental product-market fit issue.', 'SaaS cohort analysis: NRR >100% critical, best-in-class 120-140%, <90% signals PMF issue', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.95, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('MRR movement analysis should decompose MRR changes into 5 components: New MRR (new customers), Expansion MRR (upgrades), Reactivation MRR (returned churned customers), Contraction MRR (downgrades), and Churned MRR (cancellations). Healthy SaaS has Expansion MRR > Churned MRR every month. Track the ratio: Expansion/Churn should be >1.3. Below 1.0 means the business is in net revenue decline even if adding customers.', 'MRR decomposition: 5 components, expansion/churn ratio should be >1.3', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('CAC payback period by channel for B2B SaaS: organic search averages 4-6 months payback, content marketing 6-9 months, paid social 3-5 months, Google Ads 2-4 months, cold outreach 5-8 months, partner referrals 1-3 months. Track payback per channel monthly and reallocate budget to channels with <6 month payback. Include attribution modeling: last-touch overvalues paid by 40%, multi-touch is more accurate.', 'CAC payback by channel: partner referrals 1-3mo best, organic 4-6mo, reallocate to <6mo channels', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Revenue recognition for SaaS (ASC 606 / IFRS 15): annual prepayments must be recognized monthly as revenue is earned, not when cash is received. This creates a deferred revenue liability on the balance sheet. For financial planning, track both bookings (cash contracted) and recognized revenue separately. Bookings-to-revenue ratio above 1.2 indicates growing deferred revenue and future recognized revenue growth.', 'SaaS revenue recognition: separate bookings from recognized revenue, ratio >1.2 indicates growth', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Unit economics for agency services: calculate fully-loaded cost per deliverable including: direct labor (hours × rate), tool costs (proportional allocation), overhead (rent, management, admin at 15-25% of revenue), and revision buffer (add 20% to estimated hours). Price at 3x fully-loaded cost for 67% gross margin. If any service line drops below 2x markup, discontinue or restructure it within 90 days.', 'Agency unit economics: price at 3x fully-loaded cost for 67% margin, cut below 2x markup', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Cash flow forecasting for SaaS: use a 13-week rolling cash flow model updated weekly. Key inputs: contracted MRR (high certainty), pipeline MRR weighted by stage probability, planned expenses, and one-time costs. Maintain a cash runway of at least 6 months of operating expenses. The critical threshold: if runway drops below 3 months, initiate emergency cost reduction immediately. Cash burn rate should decrease quarter-over-quarter.', 'SaaS cash flow: 13-week rolling model, maintain 6-month runway, emergency at <3 months', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.95, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Pricing strategy for SaaS: value-based pricing captures 2.4x more revenue than cost-plus pricing. Calculate the economic value your product creates for the customer, then price at 10-20% of that value. If your product saves an agency 40 hours/month (valued at 4,000€), price at 400-800€/month. Review pricing annually and increase by 5-10%. Companies that adjust pricing yearly grow 2x faster than those with static pricing.', 'Value-based SaaS pricing: charge 10-20% of value created, adjust annually for 2x growth', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Gross margin optimization for SaaS: target 75-85% gross margins. Infrastructure costs (hosting, APIs) should be under 15% of revenue. Support costs should be under 10%. If infrastructure costs exceed 20%, implement usage-based pricing tiers or optimize architecture. Every 5% improvement in gross margin increases company valuation by approximately 2x the improvement in revenue terms.', 'SaaS gross margins: target 75-85%, infrastructure <15%, 5% margin improvement = 2x revenue impact on valuation', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Financial modeling for fundraising: build a bottom-up model with clear assumptions. Key metrics VCs evaluate: MRR growth rate (target >15% MoM for seed, >10% for Series A), gross margins (>70%), LTV:CAC (>3:1), NRR (>110%), and burn multiple (net burn / net new ARR, target <2). A burn multiple above 3 indicates inefficient growth. Pre-seed to Seed valuation: 30-50x ARR. Series A: 20-40x ARR.', 'VC metrics: burn multiple <2 target, seed valuation 30-50x ARR, Series A 20-40x ARR', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Tax optimization for SaaS companies in France: R&D tax credit (CIR) covers 30% of eligible R&D expenses up to 100M€, then 5% above. Eligible costs include developer salaries, subcontracted R&D (at 100% of cost), and patent filing. Young Innovative Company (JEI) status provides social charge exemptions for the first 8 years. Combine CIR + JEI for maximum benefit. Maintain detailed time-tracking logs for R&D hours as HMRC audits are common.', 'French tax optimization: CIR 30% R&D credit + JEI social charge exemptions, maintain detailed logs', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.90, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('SaaS churn cost analysis: a 1% monthly churn rate means 11.4% annual churn. Reducing monthly churn from 5% to 3% increases LTV by 67%. For a 1000-customer base at 100€/mo ARPU, reducing churn by 1 percentage point saves 12,000€/month in lost revenue. Invest up to 60% of saved revenue into churn prevention (retention team, product improvements, customer success) for positive ROI.', 'Churn economics: 1% monthly churn reduction saves 12K€/mo per 1000 customers at 100€ ARPU', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Revenue per employee benchmarks: SaaS companies targeting IPO average 200-300K€ revenue per employee. Early-stage (pre-Series A) should target 100-150K€. Agencies should target 150-200K€. Below these thresholds, either pricing is too low or team is too large. Track quarterly and take action within one quarter if trending below benchmark. The top decile SaaS companies achieve 400K€+/employee.', 'Revenue per employee: SaaS 200-300K€, agencies 150-200K€, top decile SaaS 400K€+', 'rh', 'insight', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Working capital management for agencies: invoice on project start (30-50% upfront), at midpoint (30-40%), and on completion (10-30%). Net-30 payment terms are standard but negotiate net-15 for clients under 10K€ total value. Days Sales Outstanding (DSO) should be under 45 days. Above 60 DSO, implement automated payment reminders at day 1 (invoice sent), day 25 (upcoming), day 31 (overdue), and day 45 (final notice before collections).', 'Agency working capital: 30-50% upfront invoicing, DSO under 45 days, automated reminders', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('SaaS financial dashboard KPIs: track daily: MRR, new trials, trial-to-paid conversion. Track weekly: CAC by channel, NRR, expansion revenue, support ticket volume. Track monthly: LTV:CAC, gross margin, burn rate, runway, revenue per employee. Track quarterly: Rule of 40 score, magic number, cohort retention curves, unit economics by plan. Automate all dashboards; manual tracking introduces 14% error rate and 3-day lag.', 'SaaS KPI cadence: daily MRR/trials, weekly CAC/NRR, monthly LTV/margins, quarterly Rule of 40', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Expansion revenue strategies: the easiest revenue growth comes from existing customers. Implement usage-based pricing tiers (accounts using >80% of their plan limits are expansion candidates). Introduce add-on modules priced at 20-30% of base subscription. Time upsell offers to value milestones (e.g., "You have automated 1000 posts, unlock advanced analytics"). Companies with usage-based expansion grow 37% faster than fixed-price-only models.', 'Expansion revenue: usage-based tiers, add-ons at 20-30% of base, triggers at value milestones grow 37% faster', 'commercial', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Break-even analysis for new product features: calculate development cost (team hours × loaded rate), ongoing maintenance cost (typically 20% of development cost annually), and expected revenue impact. A feature should achieve payback within 6 months through one of: direct revenue (new plan tier), indirect revenue (improved retention by X%), or cost reduction (automated process saving Y hours/month). Kill features that miss 6-month payback by >50%.', 'Feature break-even: 6-month payback target, kill features missing by >50%', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Compensation benchmarking for SaaS: engineering salaries should be 20-25% of revenue for early stage, decreasing to 15-18% at scale. Sales compensation: base salary should be 50% of OTE (on-target earnings), with OTE at 4-5x quota/OTE ratio. Marketing budget: 15-25% of revenue for growth stage, 10-15% at scale. Customer success: 5-8% of revenue. Total personnel costs should not exceed 65% of revenue.', 'SaaS compensation: engineering 20-25% of revenue early stage, total personnel <65% revenue', 'rh', 'best_practice', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Scenario planning for SaaS: build three models: base case (current growth trajectory), bull case (2x growth levers activated), bear case (50% growth reduction + major churn event). Stress-test the bear case: can the company survive 6 months with zero new revenue? If not, establish a cash reserve equal to 3 months of fixed costs. Update scenarios monthly and present to leadership quarterly.', 'SaaS scenario planning: base/bull/bear cases, stress-test 6 months zero new revenue survival', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('ARR milestones and what they unlock: 100K€ ARR validates product-market fit and enables pre-seed funding. 1M€ ARR enables Seed round and first dedicated sales hire. 5M€ ARR enables Series A and international expansion. 10M€ ARR enables Series B and market leadership investment. The median time between milestones: 100K to 1M is 18 months, 1M to 5M is 24 months, 5M to 10M is 18 months.', 'ARR milestones: 100K€ PMF, 1M€ Seed, 5M€ Series A, median 18-24mo between milestones', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Contribution margin analysis by customer segment: separate customers into segments (by plan, by acquisition channel, by industry) and calculate contribution margin for each. Segments with <40% contribution margin need either price increases or cost reduction. Often, the bottom 20% of customers by contribution margin actually lose money when including support costs. Consider implementing minimum contract values or self-serve-only tiers.', 'Contribution margin by segment: bottom 20% of customers often lose money, implement minimums', 'comptable', 'insight', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Foreign exchange risk for international SaaS: if >20% of revenue is in a different currency than costs, implement hedging. Natural hedging (matching revenue and cost currencies) is simplest. For EUR-based companies with USD revenue, price in EUR for EU clients and USD for US clients. Currency fluctuations can impact margins by 3-8% annually. Review pricing in foreign currencies semi-annually and adjust for exchange rate movements >10%.', 'FX risk: hedge when >20% revenue in different currency, review foreign pricing semi-annually', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.89, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Customer acquisition cost by motion: self-serve motion CAC averages 50-200€ (payback: 2-4 months). Sales-assisted motion CAC averages 500-2000€ (payback: 6-12 months). Enterprise motion CAC averages 5000-20000€ (payback: 12-18 months). The key is matching CAC to LTV: self-serve for LTV <2000€, sales-assisted for LTV 2000-20000€, enterprise for LTV >20000€. Mismatching motion to LTV destroys unit economics.', 'CAC by sales motion: self-serve 50-200€, sales-assisted 500-2K€, enterprise 5-20K€, match to LTV', 'commercial', 'insight', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('SaaS accounting: recognize annual subscriptions monthly (1/12 each month). Capitalize development costs (IFRS compliant) for features with >12 month useful life and amortize over the useful life period. Commission expense can be capitalized and amortized over average customer lifetime under ASC 340-40. This smooths P&L and more accurately reflects the economics. Deferred revenue is a liability, not revenue.', 'SaaS accounting: capitalize dev costs >12mo life, amortize commissions over customer lifetime', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Pricing tier architecture for SaaS: the free tier should be generous enough to demonstrate value but restrictive on the feature that power users need most. The mid tier should be the most popular (target 60% of paid customers). The high tier should be 2.5-3x the mid tier price with features that justify the premium. Include an enterprise tier with custom pricing for >100 user deployments. The mid-to-high tier upgrade rate should be 15-20%.', 'Pricing tiers: free for value demo, mid tier for 60% of customers, high tier at 2.5-3x mid price', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('EBITDA adjustments for SaaS valuation: add back one-time costs (office move, restructuring), stock-based compensation, and founder excess salary (difference between founder salary and market-rate CEO salary). Normalize for non-recurring revenue (one-time setup fees, consulting). Adjusted EBITDA gives a truer picture of recurring profitability. SaaS multiples are applied to ARR not EBITDA for high-growth (>40% YoY) companies.', 'SaaS valuation: adjust EBITDA for one-time costs, high-growth companies valued on ARR multiples', 'comptable', 'insight', 0.90, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Operating leverage in SaaS: each incremental euro of revenue should cost less to acquire and service than the last. Track the ratio of revenue growth to operating expense growth. A ratio above 1.5 indicates strong operating leverage. This means if revenue grows 30%, opex should grow less than 20%. Companies with strong operating leverage are valued at 2-3x higher multiples because they demonstrate a path to profitability.', 'Operating leverage: revenue growth / opex growth >1.5 indicates strong leverage, 2-3x higher valuations', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Customer health score financial model: assign financial risk scores based on: usage trends (declining usage = high risk), support ticket frequency (increasing = medium risk), payment behavior (late payments = high risk), and NPS score (detractor = high risk). Weight: usage 40%, support 20%, payments 20%, NPS 20%. Score <40 triggers immediate CSM outreach. Companies using health scores reduce churn by 26% and increase expansion revenue by 18%.', 'Customer health score: usage 40% weight, score <40 triggers outreach, reduces churn 26%', 'retention', 'best_practice', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Cost of delay calculation for feature development: for every month a revenue-generating feature is delayed, calculate the lost MRR opportunity. If a feature is expected to generate 10K€/month in new MRR and development takes 3 months, each month of delay costs 10K€ in potential revenue. Use cost of delay divided by development duration (CD3) to prioritize the backlog. Features with highest CD3 should always be built first.', 'Cost of delay: CD3 (cost of delay / duration) should prioritize development backlog', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Budget allocation framework for SaaS by stage: Pre-Seed (product 50%, marketing 20%, ops 30%). Seed (product 40%, marketing 30%, ops 30%). Series A (product 30%, marketing 40%, ops 30%). Series B+ (product 25%, marketing 35%, ops 40%). Marketing breakdown: 60% paid acquisition, 25% content/SEO, 15% events/partnerships. Reallocate quarterly based on channel ROI, moving 20% of budget from lowest to highest performing channels.', 'Budget allocation by SaaS stage: marketing increases from 20% pre-seed to 40% Series A', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Billing and dunning optimization: failed payment recovery can save 3-7% of MRR. Implement smart retry logic: retry failed charges on day 1, 3, 5, 7, and 14 after failure. Send email notifications at each retry. On day 7, offer to update payment method. On day 14, downgrade to free plan instead of hard cancel. Smart dunning recovers 40-60% of involuntary churn. Use machine learning to optimize retry timing based on bank patterns.', 'Dunning optimization: smart retry at days 1/3/5/7/14 recovers 40-60% of involuntary churn', 'retention', 'best_practice', 0.95, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Annual planning financial model structure: start with ARR targets, decompose into new business + expansion - churn. New business breaks down by channel with assumed conversion rates and CAC. Expansion breaks down by upgrade rate and add-on adoption. Churn breaks down by voluntary vs involuntary. Build headcount plan from revenue targets: sales quota coverage should be 3-4x OTE. Budget with 10% contingency for unplanned expenses.', 'Annual planning: decompose ARR into new/expansion/churn, sales quota 3-4x OTE coverage, 10% contingency', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Profitability analysis for marketing channels: calculate fully-loaded ROAS including: ad spend, creative production cost, landing page development, attribution tool costs, and team time. Most companies undercount true CAC by 30-40% by ignoring indirect costs. A channel showing 3:1 ROAS on ad spend alone might only be 1.8:1 fully loaded. Only channels with fully-loaded ROAS above 2:1 should receive increased budget.', 'Marketing ROAS: include indirect costs, true CAC is 30-40% higher than ad-spend-only calculation', 'marketing', 'insight', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Discount policy financial impact: offering 20% annual discounts for upfront payment improves cash flow but reduces LTV by 20% if no additional retention benefit. The financial breakeven for annual discounts: the discount percentage must be less than (monthly churn rate × 12) to be net positive. If monthly churn is 3% (36% annual), a 20% annual discount is profitable. If monthly churn is 1.5% (18% annual), a 20% discount destroys value.', 'Discount economics: annual discount must be less than annual churn rate to be profitable', 'commercial', 'insight', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Inventory of metrics for board reporting: slide 1: ARR waterfall (beginning ARR + new + expansion - contraction - churn = ending ARR). Slide 2: unit economics (LTV, CAC, LTV:CAC, payback). Slide 3: growth efficiency (burn multiple, magic number, Rule of 40). Slide 4: operational (NRR, logo retention, NPS). Slide 5: pipeline and forecast. Slide 6: cash position and runway. Update monthly, present quarterly.', 'Board reporting: 6 key slides covering ARR waterfall through cash position, monthly updates', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Employee cost modeling for hiring plan: in France, employer total cost is approximately 1.45x gross salary (including social charges at 42-45% of gross). Budget also for: equipment (2-3K€/employee), tools/licenses (500-1K€/month/employee), office space (500-800€/month/employee in major cities), and training (1-2% of payroll). A developer with 50K€ gross salary actually costs approximately 80K€ fully loaded.', 'French hiring costs: 1.45x gross salary, 50K€ gross = ~80K€ fully loaded', 'rh', 'best_practice', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Revenue forecasting accuracy: use weighted pipeline method. Multiply each opportunity by its stage probability: lead (5%), qualified (15%), demo completed (30%), proposal sent (50%), negotiation (70%), verbal commit (90%). Sum for expected revenue. Forecast accuracy should be within 10% of actual for the current month, 20% for next month, 30% for the quarter. Track forecast accuracy to improve stage probability assumptions over time.', 'Revenue forecasting: stage-weighted pipeline, target 10% accuracy current month, track and improve', 'commercial', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Gross margin by product line analysis: most SaaS companies have multiple product lines (core platform, add-ons, services, API). Calculate gross margin per product line separately. Core platform should maintain >80% margins. API/usage-based features typically have 50-65% margins due to compute costs. Professional services should target 40-50% margins. Weight overall gross margin accordingly and protect high-margin product lines from feature creep that increases costs.', 'Gross margin by product: core platform >80%, API 50-65%, services 40-50%', 'comptable', 'insight', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Debt vs equity financing for SaaS: revenue-based financing (RBF) costs 6-12% total repayment premium and maintains ownership. It is suitable for companies with >50K€ MRR and >75% gross margins. Venture debt costs 8-15% annually plus warrants (0.5-2% equity). It is suitable post-Series A with 12+ months runway. Equity (VC) dilutes 15-25% per round but provides strategic value and no repayment obligation. Use RBF for growth acceleration, not survival.', 'SaaS financing: RBF at >50K€ MRR for growth, venture debt post-Series A, VC for strategic value', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.90, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Month-end financial close process for SaaS: Day 1-2: reconcile bank accounts and recognize revenue. Day 3-4: accrue expenses and close payroll. Day 5: generate financial statements (P&L, balance sheet, cash flow). Day 6-7: prepare variance analysis (actual vs budget). Day 8-10: prepare management reporting with KPIs. Close within 10 business days. Automate reconciliation and recognition to reduce close to 5 days. Fast close correlates with better decision-making.', 'Month-end close: 10-day target, automate to 5 days, variance analysis on day 6-7', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.92, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Pricing page conversion optimization from a financial perspective: show pricing in the local currency (increases conversion 12% versus showing USD to EU visitors). Display annual pricing by default with monthly as a toggle (increases annual plan selection 34%). Show the savings amount in euros, not percentages ("Save 238€/year" outperforms "Save 17%"). Include a money-back guarantee (reduces refund requests by 14% paradoxically).', 'Pricing page: local currency +12% conversion, euro savings amount beats percentages, money-back guarantee reduces refunds 14%', 'commercial', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Financial impact of customer success: companies with dedicated CSM teams have 24% lower churn, 31% higher NRR, and 18% higher customer satisfaction. The optimal CSM:customer ratio depends on ACV: for ACV <1K€, use tech-touch (1 CSM per 500 accounts). For ACV 1-10K€, use low-touch (1 CSM per 100 accounts). For ACV >10K€, use high-touch (1 CSM per 20-30 accounts). CSM team should be self-funding through retained and expanded revenue.', 'Customer success ROI: 24% lower churn, CSM ratio by ACV, self-funding through retention', 'retention', 'insight', 0.94, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Vendor and tool cost optimization: audit SaaS tool spend quarterly. The average company wastes 25-30% on unused or underutilized licenses. Negotiate annual contracts for tools representing >500€/month spend. Consolidate overlapping tools (the average 50-person company uses 3-4 project management tools). Set auto-alerts when any tool cost exceeds 2% of revenue. Total tooling costs should be 8-12% of revenue for early-stage SaaS.', 'Tool cost optimization: 25-30% typically wasted on unused licenses, total tooling should be 8-12% of revenue', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Financial metrics for the CEO dashboard: primary metrics updated daily: MRR, daily active users, trial-to-paid conversion rate, support response time. Secondary metrics updated weekly: CAC, NRR, pipeline value, cash position. Strategic metrics updated monthly: Rule of 40, LTV:CAC, burn multiple, revenue per employee. Use traffic-light indicators (green/yellow/red) with automatic alerts when any metric crosses the yellow threshold.', 'CEO dashboard: daily MRR/DAU, weekly CAC/NRR, monthly Rule of 40/LTV:CAC, traffic light alerts', 'ceo', 'best_practice', 0.93, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('SaaS valuation multiples 2025-2026: growth rate >50% commands 15-25x ARR. Growth 30-50% commands 10-15x ARR. Growth 15-30% commands 5-10x ARR. Growth <15% commands 3-5x ARR. These multiples apply to Series A and beyond. For acquisitions, EBITDA multiples are also used: profitable SaaS companies trade at 15-25x EBITDA. Apply a 20-30% illiquidity discount for private companies versus public comparables.', 'SaaS valuations: >50% growth = 15-25x ARR, profitable SaaS = 15-25x EBITDA, 20-30% private discount', 'ceo', 'insight', 0.91, 'elite_batch_54', 'system'),
('Financial controls for growing companies: implement segregation of duties when team exceeds 5 people (the person who approves expenses should not be the person who processes payments). Set approval thresholds: <500€ manager approval, <5K€ director approval, <20K€ VP approval, >20K€ CEO approval. Monthly expense audits catch an average of 3-5% in unauthorized or erroneous spend. Implement automated receipt capture from day one.', 'Financial controls: segregation of duties at 5+ people, tiered approvals, monthly audits catch 3-5% errors', 'comptable', 'best_practice', 0.90, 'elite_batch_54', 'system')
